{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2e82ea4d-4cdb-4d9f-89a8-d570bf4c8f57","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_015FsbvkwsXxK6zLCABTxmQU","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Configuring NativeAOT crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_013jvPxWSYXxpWwaraJYoUfT","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-3738497ea9ab43af9b21348d41d4ab31"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-3738497ea9ab43af9b21348d41d4ab31."}],"interactionId":"5a843b73-470b-49b5-9213-5de4f28ce81a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` installed at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me look at what's in the current working directory and check if there are any existing configurations or documentation related to this.\n\nLet me think about what's needed:\n\n1. For .NET NativeAOT apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps. The environment variables needed are different.\n2. For NativeAOT in .NET 8+, the crash dump support uses `createdump` but requires specific environment variables.\n\n\n3. I need to set up the right environment variables: `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` to enable mini dump collection, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType` to specify the dump type (1 for mini, 2 for heap, 3 for triage, 4 for full), and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` to define where the dumps get written. There's also `DOTNET_CreateDumpDiagnostics` for enabling diagnostics on createdump itself, and for NativeAOT I should check if `DOTNET_EnableCrashReport` is needed.\n\nActually, let me clarify the NativeAOT-specific setup: `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName` with a path pattern like `/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t` work, along with `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` for full dumps. The critical part for NativeAOT is that the runtime won't automatically locate createdump, so I need to explicitly set `DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath` to point to where createdump is installed.\n\nFor Kubernetes, I also need to think about the infrastructure side—setting up an emptyDir or persistent volume for the dumps to land in, configuring resource limits appropriately, and ensuring the container has the right permissions to write the dump files.","outputTokens":717,"requestId":"7842:1479F8:4B05C4:5668C4:69FA9DAE"},"id":"1c0f24ba-b037-4767-96ad-86644c8c11ce","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:47:41.935Z","parentId":"547a47ab-32c4-43ee-9e90-f365fa627b0f"}
